<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1770,2011]" pageId="6" pageNumber="196">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1878,1903]" pageId="6" pageNumber="196">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[329,417,1878,1902]" class="Insecta" family="Macroveliidae" genus="Xiphovelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="196" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulva" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[329,417,1878,1902]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="196">X. fulva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[425,516,1878,1903]" pageId="6" pageNumber="196">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[425,516,1878,1903]" pageId="6" pageNumber="196" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be distinguished with its closely related 
<taxonomicName box="[1028,1137,1878,1902]" class="Insecta" family="Macroveliidae" genus="Xiphovelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="196" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis box="[1028,1137,1878,1902]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="196">X. glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by relatively shorter body length (
<number box="[236,350,1914,1939]" pageId="6" pageNumber="196" value="1.54" valueMax="1.55" valueMin="1.53">1.53–1.55</number>
) (
<figureCitation box="[374,442,1914,1939]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1950,1973]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,193,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[183,1403,193,1930]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 10. Habitus of Xiphovelia spp .. 5 – 7. X. denigrata sp. nov. (5. apterous male; 6. macropterous male; 7. apterous female); 8 – 10. X. fulva sp. nov. (8. apterous male; 9. macropterous male; 10. macropterous female). Scale 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244014/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="196">
Fig. 
<number box="[427,442,1915,1939]" pageId="6" pageNumber="196" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
); head dorsum yellowish brown (
<figureCitation box="[819,886,1914,1939]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1950,1973]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,193,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[183,1403,193,1930]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 10. Habitus of Xiphovelia spp .. 5 – 7. X. denigrata sp. nov. (5. apterous male; 6. macropterous male; 7. apterous female); 8 – 10. X. fulva sp. nov. (8. apterous male; 9. macropterous male; 10. macropterous female). Scale 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244014/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="196">
Fig. 
<number box="[871,886,1915,1939]" pageId="6" pageNumber="196" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
); position of silvery hair markings on abdominal tergites (laterally on mediotergum II, medially on mediotergites III 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[907,921,1950,1975]" pageId="6" pageNumber="196">–</emphasis>
VII, and inner region on laterotergites III and VI); the ear-like process on each side of pygophore much wider in caudal view (
<figureCitation box="[1050,1134,1986,2011]" captionStart="FIGURES 21 – 29" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1901,1924]" captionTargetBox="[213,1372,1325,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[203,1384,1319,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 21 – 29. Abdominal segment VIII and pygophore of Xiphovelia spp. (males). 21 – 25, abdominal segment VIII (21. X. glauca Esaki &amp; Miyamoto, 1959; 22. X. denigrata sp. nov., ventral view; 23. X. denigrata sp. nov., ventrolateral view; 24. X. fulva sp. nov.; 25. X. reflexa sp. nov.); 26 – 29, pygophore in dorsal view (26. X. glauca Esaki &amp; Miyamoto, 1959; 27. X. denigrata sp. nov.; 28. X. fulva sp. nov.; 29. X. reflexa sp. nov.). Scale 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/244016/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="196">
Fig. 
<number box="[1102,1134,1987,2011]" pageId="6" pageNumber="196" value="28.0">28</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
